<i>to conduct a large
excavation in the area.</i>

12:10.396 --> 12:11.896
(Gary mutters)

12:16.393 --> 12:17.819
(beeping)

12:17.903 --> 12:20.146
Well, that sounds good, mate.

12:20.230 --> 12:23.241
This little baby wants
to be rescued. Just there.

12:31.500 --> 12:34.085
All right.
Let's recheck the hole.

12:34.170 --> 12:36.913
It got stronger.
I like the sound of this.

12:36.997 --> 12:39.048
Let's see if I can pinpoint it.

12:40.417 --> 12:41.918
(beeping)

12:42.002 --> 12:43.428
There it is.

12:43.512 --> 12:44.763
Wow! Look at that.

12:46.348 --> 12:48.516
Big old iron spike.

12:48.601 --> 12:51.677
That is heavy as well,
that's an oldie.

12:51.762 --> 12:54.180
I mean, this is chunky iron,

12:54.264 --> 12:56.182
just up from
the shoreline like this,

12:56.266 --> 12:58.693
I have no idea the use of it.

12:58.778 --> 13:02.781
So, Dr. Brosseau,
XRF, get it cleaned,

13:02.940 --> 13:05.366
get it conserved,
and see what it says.

13:05.526 --> 13:06.785
Yeah. And get Carmen Legge

13:06.869 --> 13:08.611
- to have a gander at it as well.
- Yup.

13:08.704 --> 13:10.780
<i>RICK:
I have a special place</i>

13:10.864 --> 13:13.291
<i>for Zena Halpern
and her research,</i>

13:13.375 --> 13:17.954
but we are still trying
to understand the map.

13:18.038 --> 13:19.798
All right, mate.
Let's keep gridding.

13:19.882 --> 13:23.876
<i>RICK:
To prove the significance of it,</i>

13:23.969 --> 13:27.713
we've got to find and hold
evidence in our hand that

13:27.798 --> 13:29.974
these things exist,
well and truly exist.

13:36.139 --> 13:38.316
(beeping)

13:38.400 --> 13:40.819
Two-way repeatable signal.

13:42.062 --> 13:44.230
That's a little screamer.

13:44.323 --> 13:46.157
Just there, mate.

13:49.736 --> 13:51.404
My lucky digger's on fire!

13:51.497 --> 13:52.997
(Rick chuckles)

14:03.342 --> 14:06.419
Hopefully it's still
in the hole, mate.

14:06.512 --> 14:09.005
- (beeping)
- It is.

14:09.089 --> 14:10.673
Come on, me little beauty.

14:10.757 --> 14:12.350
(chuckles)

14:13.686 --> 14:15.761
Ooh. Look at that.

14:15.855 --> 14:16.855
That is...

14:17.014 --> 14:19.181
- That looks like a...
- Like a tool?

14:19.275 --> 14:21.851
GARY:
Yeah. Is it an old adze?

14:21.944 --> 14:23.778
- Could be.
- I mean, we find all that

14:23.863 --> 14:26.856
wood with the bark,
the old timbers.

14:26.949 --> 14:29.108
That's what it looks
like to me, maybe,

14:29.201 --> 14:30.451
- an adze?
- Yup.

14:30.536 --> 14:32.620
<i>NARRATOR:
A possible adze?</i>

14:32.779 --> 14:34.372
Discovered on Lot 4?

14:35.616 --> 14:38.284
<i>Dating back to the times
of ancient Egypt,</i>

14:38.368 --> 14:42.046
<i>an adze is a type of cutting
tool featuring a sharp edge</i>

14:42.205 --> 14:44.883
<i>that runs perpendicular
to its handle</i>

14:45.042 --> 14:47.376
<i>and was designed for use
in ship building</i>

14:47.469 --> 14:49.879
<i>or detailed woodwork
on structures.</i>

14:51.214 --> 14:54.967
<i>If this tool proves to be
an adze, as Gary believes,</i>

14:55.052 --> 14:57.395
<i>could it be connected
to some kind of structure</i>

14:57.554 --> 15:00.306
<i>that was built
long ago in this area?</i>

15:00.390 --> 15:03.151
<i>RICK:
If some activity on Lot 4</i>

15:03.310 --> 15:04.560
<i>was done long ago,</i>

15:04.645 --> 15:06.312
<i>they would need to shape timbers</i>

15:06.405 --> 15:09.574
<i>in order to do cribbing
of the underground works.</i>

15:09.658 --> 15:12.577
I-I don't know a whole lot
about an adze, you know,

15:12.661 --> 15:14.662
but I know it's used
for shaping wood.

15:14.747 --> 15:16.238
<i>That's interesting.</i>

15:16.323 --> 15:18.658
I love these interesting finds.

15:18.742 --> 15:21.911
And we're getting more and more
interesting finds on Lot 4.

15:21.995 --> 15:23.329
- But that is really cool.
- It's a curious find.

15:23.413 --> 15:24.747
- Yeah.
- It's a very curious find.

15:24.831 --> 15:27.500
This and that nice
old piece of iron,

15:27.584 --> 15:31.170
that spike, whatever it is,
can easily be dated.

15:31.254 --> 15:33.589
They're both interesting enough
to warrant that,

15:33.674 --> 15:35.099
- that's for sure.
- Yeah, for sure, mate.

15:35.258 --> 15:39.437
<i>I think we have ended the day
on a high with this note.</i>

15:39.521 --> 15:40.939
<i>RICK:
I agree.</i>

15:43.943 --> 15:45.401
<i>NARRATOR:
The following day...</i>

15:50.783 --> 15:52.742
(horn honking)

15:53.777 --> 15:56.120
- Here it is, guys.
- There it is.

15:58.707 --> 16:00.032
<i>ALEX:
Oh, man. Look at that.</i>

16:00.117 --> 16:02.460
<i>(laughs)</i>

16:02.544 --> 16:06.622
<i>Alex Lagina, Oak Island
historian Charles Barkhouse,</i>

16:06.707 --> 16:09.133
<i>and heavy equipment operator
Billy Gerhardt</i>

16:09.218 --> 16:14.714
<i>gather near the swamp to receive
a 35-ton long-reach excavator.</i>

16:14.807 --> 16:16.724
<i>ALEX: Look at that!
That's really something.</i>

16:16.809 --> 16:19.719
<i>- BILLY: That's a long junk of stuff, yeah.
- (Alex laughs)</i>

16:19.812 --> 16:21.637
ALEX: You don't appreciate it
until it kind of turns

16:21.722 --> 16:24.390
- and goes past ya.
- Exactly.

16:24.474 --> 16:26.901
<i>NARRATOR: With the capability
of reaching up to 80 feet</i>

16:26.986 --> 16:28.653
<i>out into the swamp,</i>

16:28.812 --> 16:30.479
<i>and to much deeper depths
than they've been able</i>

16:30.564 --> 16:32.148
<i>to dig in this area before...</i>

16:32.232 --> 16:35.234
- ALEX: Oh, yeah.
<i>- it is the team's hope</i>

16:35.327 --> 16:37.161
<i>to not only find more evidence
that could help</i>

16:37.320 --> 16:39.488
<i>prove Fred Nolan's
incredible theory</i>

16:39.573 --> 16:42.241
<i>but also anything of value</i>

16:42.325 --> 16:45.503
<i>that might lie buried
beneath the muck and mud.</i>

16:45.587 --> 16:49.749
We have a number of items
that we believe,

16:49.833 --> 16:51.834
from a layman's perspective,

16:51.918 --> 16:53.669
<i>can be associated with a ship,</i>

16:53.754 --> 16:55.513
<i>or the building of ships, even.</i>

16:55.672 --> 16:56.931
- CHARLES: Hey, guys.
<i>- MARTY: So now</i>

16:57.016 --> 16:58.516
<i>we're digging
to see what's there.</i>

16:58.600 --> 17:00.342
<i>And hopefully find
some information</i>

17:00.427 --> 17:02.520
that puts this whole
puzzle together.

17:02.679 --> 17:04.847
- Nice machine, Billy.
- Yes, it is, Marty.

17:04.940 --> 17:07.358
- Hi, guys.
- MARTY: Hey, Charles.

17:07.443 --> 17:08.943
- You ready?
- CHARLES: Absolutely.

17:09.028 --> 17:10.269
I was just wondering
where to start.

17:10.353 --> 17:12.021
You like starting here?
Rick likes starting here?

17:12.114 --> 17:14.523
- Yeah.
- Let Gary figure out

17:14.616 --> 17:15.608
where he wants
the material laid down.

17:15.701 --> 17:18.444
We have to lay eyes
on this, because

17:18.537 --> 17:21.363
the number of finds
we've made that are wooden...

17:21.457 --> 17:22.457
There's something in there,

17:22.541 --> 17:23.783
- I think.
- Right.

17:23.867 --> 17:26.044
- Yeah.
- Put it where you want it to go, Billy,

17:26.128 --> 17:27.879
- and let's take a few shovelfuls.
- Yep.

17:27.963 --> 17:29.881
- It's time to dig.
- BILLY: Time to dig.

17:39.549 --> 17:40.549
Ready to go?

17:40.634 --> 17:42.393
GARY: Yep! Ready to rock
and roll, Billy.

17:44.229 --> 17:45.888
Here we go, ready for

17:45.981 --> 17:47.565
- some slop.
- CHARLES: Oh, yeah.

17:48.975 --> 17:52.645
<i>NARRATOR: While Billy begins
digging with the long-range excavator,</i>

17:52.738 --> 17:56.407
<i>Marty Lagina uses
a smaller, 13-ton excavator</i>

17:56.492 --> 17:59.243
<i>to clear water away from
the area as it accumulates.</i>

18:00.487 --> 18:03.155
<i>Meanwhile,
Gary Drayton will scan</i>

18:03.240 --> 18:07.752
<i>the spoils for any potential
metal clues... or valuables.</i>

18:07.836 --> 18:10.579
I don't know that
there's a quote-un-quote

18:10.664 --> 18:12.832
treasure chest,
or-or, or something that

18:12.916 --> 18:14.917
can be retrieved from
the body of the swamp.

18:15.001 --> 18:18.337
<i>But Mr. Nolan did find
some ship parts there,</i>

18:18.421 --> 18:23.259
<i>and his beliefs are now
being validated because</i>

18:23.343 --> 18:25.436
<i>we are finding ship items.</i>

18:25.521 --> 18:28.931
So, if there is a ship there,
then I want to see the evidence.

18:29.015 --> 18:32.777
I want to prove
that, indeed, uh...

18:32.936 --> 18:35.196
at the bottom of the swamp
there is a ship.

18:35.280 --> 18:36.864
We don't have
that information yet.

18:37.023 --> 18:38.691
You want to walk in there?

18:38.775 --> 18:40.409
GARY:
Uh... Yeah. Please.

18:42.362 --> 18:44.789
That'd be great.
There we go. Thanks.

18:49.128 --> 18:50.795
- CHARLES: See all this water here?
- ALEX: Yeah.

18:50.954 --> 18:52.421
CHARLES: The trench is
starting to silt up.

18:57.386 --> 19:00.555
Look at that.
There she goes.

19:00.639 --> 19:02.223
- CHALRES: Yeah.
- LAIRD: Hey, guys.

19:02.307 --> 19:03.724
- Hey, Laird.
- GARY: Hey, mate.

19:03.809 --> 19:06.227
Requested a shovel.
How are things going?

19:06.311 --> 19:07.970
Well, it's just
getting going now.

19:08.054 --> 19:09.147
We're getting to deeper layers.

19:09.231 --> 19:10.815
- Okay.
- Now we're going

19:10.899 --> 19:12.641
to try to get the majority

19:12.726 --> 19:14.152
of that water to get moving.

19:14.311 --> 19:16.237
Marty's clearing
the ditch a little bit.

19:16.321 --> 19:18.647
- LAIRD: Okay.
- RICK: So, the hope is that

19:18.740 --> 19:20.316
we can continue
to move that way,

19:20.409 --> 19:22.234
towards the areas
that we have...

19:22.319 --> 19:24.078
Yeah, this all falls within

19:24.237 --> 19:25.571
- the permit that we have.
- Yes.

19:25.655 --> 19:27.573
Yes. Nothing there, Gary?

19:27.657 --> 19:29.292
No. Nothing.

19:37.259 --> 19:39.168
ALEX:
That does not look like a...

19:39.261 --> 19:41.345
- RICK: Oh.
- ALEX: That's a pretty big log.

19:41.430 --> 19:43.181
CHARLES:
Got a big log in here, Billy!

19:49.605 --> 19:51.189
- RICK: It's huge.
- CHARLES: Yeah.

19:51.273 --> 19:53.182
<i>NARRATOR: At the southern edge
of the triangle-shaped swamp,</i>

19:53.275 --> 19:55.851
<i>the Oak Island team
has just made</i>

19:55.944 --> 19:57.653
<i>a potentially important
discovery.</i>

19:58.855 --> 20:01.616
- RICK: That's a big stump.
- BILLY: Yeah.

20:01.775 --> 20:04.785
- RICK: How deep was that?
- Four to six.

20:05.946 --> 20:07.538
I think that's the root
at the bottom, right?

20:07.623 --> 20:09.540
- Over here?
- I think so. Yeah.

20:15.297 --> 20:17.465
RICK:
It's pretty big, whatever it is.

20:17.624 --> 20:19.175
BILLY:
The color is like oak.

20:22.638 --> 20:25.798
- Did you do this, Gary?
- Yeah, I did it. Yeah.

20:25.891 --> 20:28.133
No metal hits in that.

20:29.219 --> 20:31.804
RICK: Well, it was
four to six feet down.

20:31.888 --> 20:34.640
I mean, that says
something about dry--

20:34.733 --> 20:35.983
It being dry land.

20:36.068 --> 20:37.559
- Yeah.
- And then, somehow,

20:37.644 --> 20:40.404
four feet of organics went over

20:40.563 --> 20:42.490
the top of it
and then it became a wetland.

20:42.574 --> 20:43.741
Yeah.

20:43.900 --> 20:46.735
<i>NARRATOR:
A possible oak tree stump?</i>

20:46.828 --> 20:49.247
<i>Found in the southern region
of the swamp?</i>

20:49.406 --> 20:51.991
<i>Because oak trees
cannot grow naturally</i>

20:52.075 --> 20:53.751
<i>in water environments,</i>

20:53.910 --> 20:56.254
<i>could Rick be correct
that this stump offers</i>

20:56.338 --> 20:59.748
<i>more evidence that the swamp
was artificially made,</i>

20:59.833 --> 21:02.551
<i>just like the late Fred Nolan
strongly believed?</i>

21:03.586 --> 21:06.505
RICK: At one time,
that had to be

21:06.589 --> 21:08.841
- forestland, right?
- Yeah. Yeah.

21:08.925 --> 21:11.102
A tree of this size
would not be rooted,

21:11.261 --> 21:12.270
unless it were dry.

21:12.354 --> 21:15.022
<i>It may provide
a certain date as to</i>

21:15.181 --> 21:17.766
<i>when the swamp became a swamp.</i>

21:17.859 --> 21:20.111
And it may be able
to tell a story.

21:22.698 --> 21:25.616
I'd love to see
a 500-year representation

21:25.775 --> 21:28.869
- of what this may have looked like.
- Mm.

21:28.954 --> 21:31.447
LAIRD: And that could help
explain some of the other things

21:31.531 --> 21:33.291
that are happening around here.

21:33.375 --> 21:38.296
If that's the root, you cut it,
figure out how old it is, first,

21:38.455 --> 21:40.372
and then draw your
interpretation from there.

21:40.457 --> 21:42.466
- Right?
- Yeah. Yeah.

21:42.551 --> 21:45.428
<i>RICK: It'd be nice to know
how old that is.</i>

21:47.723 --> 21:49.724
<i>NARRATOR:
Later that afternoon...</i>

21:49.808 --> 21:51.892
<i>CHARLES: What's the good
word there, Adam?</i>

21:51.977 --> 21:53.719
- 109.
- 109. Chips and chunks.

21:53.812 --> 21:54.887
Just chips and chunks.

21:54.980 --> 21:57.139
<i>while the operations
in the swamp</i>

21:57.232 --> 21:59.400
<i>and the Money Pit area
continue...</i>

22:00.477 --> 22:02.394
<i>RICK: I always
like coming here.</i>

22:02.479 --> 22:03.729
I like talking to this guy.

22:03.813 --> 22:05.072
ALEX: Yeah.
Really interesting.

22:05.157 --> 22:07.742
<i>NARRATOR: some 50 miles
north of Oak Island,</i>

22:07.901 --> 22:10.578
<i>in Centreville, Nova Scotia...</i>

22:10.737 --> 22:13.572
- Hey, Carmen.
- Hey, Carmen!

22:13.665 --> 22:15.991
- ALEX: We're back again.
<i>- Marty Lagina, his son Alex,</i>

22:16.084 --> 22:19.078
<i>and Jack Begley
arrive at Northville Farm.</i>

22:19.162 --> 22:20.746
- Got some goodies?
- ALEX: We do.

22:20.830 --> 22:22.164
- MARTY: We hope so.
- All right.

22:22.257 --> 22:23.665
- Let's have a look at them.
- Yeah.

22:23.759 --> 22:26.677
<i>NARRATOR: They are eager
to have blacksmithing expert</i>

22:26.836 --> 22:29.013
<i>Carmen Legge examine
the believed ancient</i>

22:29.172 --> 22:31.932
<i>adze cutting tool
that Rick and Gary Drayton</i>

22:32.092 --> 22:34.185
<i>recently discovered on Lot 4.</i>

22:35.771 --> 22:37.930
ALEX:
So, this was found on Lot 4,

22:38.014 --> 22:39.774
which is on the north side
of the island.

22:39.858 --> 22:41.192
CARMEN: Okay.

23:01.380 --> 23:02.380
And you just kinda
scrape it along?

23:05.625 --> 23:06.801
Oh, okay.

23:06.885 --> 23:07.843
But it, um...

23:19.398 --> 23:20.564
Yeah.

23:30.567 --> 23:31.742
Um...

23:41.420 --> 23:42.744
- Those are good numbers.
- Yeah.

23:42.829 --> 23:43.912
CARMEN:
It is. Yeah.

23:43.997 --> 23:46.757
<i>NARRATOR: An English-style adze?</i>

23:46.916 --> 23:49.844
<i>Dating back more than
150 years prior to</i>

23:50.003 --> 23:51.670
<i>the discovery of the Money Pit?</i>

23:51.763 --> 23:56.183
<i>If so, what might it have
been used for on Oak Island?</i>

23:56.268 --> 23:59.103
<i>And specifically, on Lot 4?</i>

24:00.263 --> 24:02.598
Are there any houses
or homesteads over there?

24:02.682 --> 24:03.682
There's no-- I don't think
there's ever been

24:03.775 --> 24:05.526
anything constructed on Lot 4.

24:05.685 --> 24:09.947
If you had an expedition
to sink a shaft,

24:10.106 --> 24:12.274
for whatever reason,
you would need timbers.

24:12.358 --> 24:15.369
- Yes.
- And you'd want them to fit together well.

24:15.454 --> 24:17.529
- Yes.
- So, you might need such a tool.

24:17.614 --> 24:19.698
You send your crew over there,
"I need...

24:19.782 --> 24:22.201
I need 400 six-by-sixes."

24:22.285 --> 24:23.878
Whatever.
"And they better fit."

24:24.037 --> 24:25.129
Then you'd need that, right?

24:25.213 --> 24:26.955
- You would use a tool like this.
- MARTY: Yeah.

24:27.048 --> 24:29.208
- For the cribbing?
- MARTY: Exactly.

24:29.301 --> 24:32.386
I'm actually glad that we're
looking closer at Lot 4.

24:32.545 --> 24:34.129
Man, that's a bit of a mystery.

24:34.214 --> 24:35.797
<i>This is an adze.</i>

24:35.882 --> 24:37.633
<i>I mean, he's absolutely sure.</i>

24:37.717 --> 24:40.385
<i>It's old and it's corroded,
